'''Alexandre Camille Taponier''' (2 February 1749&ndash;13 April 1831) commanded an infantry division in several battles during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]]. He joined the [[French Royal Army (1652-1830)|French Royal Army]] in 1767. He became a [[chef de bataillon]] on 15 October 1793 and a [[general of division]] less than two months later on 7 November, a speed of promotion that is astonishing. He led his division at the end of 1793 in the battles of [[Battle of Kaiserslautern|Kaiserslautern]], [[Battle of Froeschwiller (1793)|Froeschwiller]] and [[Second Battle of Wissembourg (1793)|Second Wissembourg]].

He led a division at the [[Siege of Luxembourg (1794–1795)|Siege of Luxembourg]] in 1794&ndash;1795 and at [[Battle of Ettlingen|Ettlingen]] and [[Battle of Neresheim (1796)|Neresheim]] in 1796. That summer, army commander [[Jean Victor Marie Moreau]] forced him to resign after accusing him of demanding irregular contributions. Placed on active service again, he commanded the 13th Military Division for a few months in 1799&ndash;1800. He became a member of the [[Légion d'Honneur]] in 1805 but was not employed during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and retired from military service in 1811 at age 62. Taponier is one of the [[names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe]] on Column 5.

